ε’ Bacon appears to hare adopted a theory of the ultimate constitution of matter, in some respects similar to that of the lltomists (see especially Bk. 11. Aph. 8); and hence his partiality for the school of Democritus. He rejected, however, the hypothesis of a vacuum, and it does not appear whether his atoms (or rather particles, as he preferred to call them) differed in material or only in shape and arrangement. Any way, all mate- rial objects, he conceived, if only we could penetrate to their ultimate structure or constitution, would be found to consist of a number of small particles, arranged in some definite manner with reference to each other. .· This arrangement, as it escapes detection, is called Larem Schemarr'smas, '⁴ and any change iu it is termed Meta-Schemarismus,· moreorer, as the ¹ hrtemal process by which such change takes place is unknown to us, it is called Larem Processus.
